learning2014 dataset is a subset of JYTOPKYS3 dataset containing 7 variables:

  1. gender
  2. age
  3. attitude
  4. deep (deep questions): combined of 12 variables from the original data set (starting with D letter)
  5. stra (strategic questions): combined of 8 variables from the original data set (starting with ST)
  6. suf (surface questions): combined of 12 variables from the original data set (starting with SU)
  7. points: from statistics course exam

deep, stra, and suf are calculated by combining and averaging their corresponding variables.

In the first model, we have used three explanatory variables of attitude, stra, and deep. According to the summary, there is no significant relationship between deep and points. Thus, we removed deep variable from the model, and fit the model again with attitude and stra as the explanatory variables; still, it seems stra has not statistically significant relationship with our target variable, points. So, we fit the model once again with only attitude as its explanatory variable. The summary shows a significant linear relationship between attitude and points which means those who have positive attitude toward statistics, get better points in this course.

4. Parameter interpretaion

Using the summary of fitted model, multiple R-squared in all three level, is low which indicates a weak relationship between our explanatory variables and points. However only one of these weak estimating relationship (between attitude and points) is significant.

5. diagnostic plots

library(ggfortify)

The assumptions of linear regression are: - The relationship between the predictor (x) and the outcome (y) is assumed to be linear. - The residual errors are assumed to be normally distributed. - The residuals are assumed to have a constant variance (homoscedasticity) - residuals error terms are independent.

We have checked the above assumptions by diagnostic plots. Residual vs Fitted plot is without pattern that shows the relationship between variables (attitude and points) is linear. Normal Q-Q plot follows a straight line which shows residuals have normally distributed. From Residuals vs Leverage plot, we see there is only three influential/extreme values in the data (#71, #35, #56)

the alc data set contains 370 rows and 35 columns. We generated this data set through combining the two data sets from secondary school students in math class and portuguese language class regarding their study performance. We did this combination by removing the free columns which varied in two data sets, and keeping the common columns in two data sets. Now, our joined/combined data set have 35 variables.

Task 3

dependent variable: high/low alcohol consumption (high_use) explanatory variables: school absences, age, family relationships (famrel), going out with friends (goout) hypothesis:

  • school absences is more prevalent among students who consume more alcohol.
  • Older students consume more alcohol compare to youngers.
  • student who highly consume alcohol, have worse relationship with their family.
  • student who highly consume alcohol, spent more time out with friends.

According to the logistic regression model, we got more accurate outcomes regarding the relationship between our variables:

  • There is a significant predictor relationship between school absences and high alcohol consumption. The odds ratio is 1.07 which is in the confidence interval (1.03 - 1.12). P-value is 0.001 that indicates the relationship is significant. So, our hypothesis is confirmed. Those who consumes more alcohol are more likely to be absent at school.
  • Our model shows there is no significant relationship between age and alcohol consumption. Although the odds ratio is 1.08 which is in the confidence interval (0.87 - 1.35), P-value (which is 0.45) does not show significant relationship. Thus, our hypothesis is rejected.
  • The third hypothesis is true. There is a significant negative relationship between alcohol consumption and family relationship. The odds ratio (0.68) is in the confidence interval (0.52 - 0.89) and P-value (0.005) is significant. Also, the estimate value is -0.37 which indicates negative relationship. It means those who consumes more alcohol probably have worse relationship with their families.
  • The most significant is shown between high alcohol consumption and going out with friends. The odds ratio is 2.14 which is at the middle of the confidence interval (1.69-2.73). P-value is 3.8e-10 and estimate value is 0.76 show a strong significant relationship between alcohol consumption and goout variable. Our model confirmed our hypothesis that those who consume more alcohol are more likely to spend more time outdoor.

Task 6

# Work with the exercise in this chunk, step-by-step. Fix the R code!
# alc is available

# fit the model
model <- glm(high_use ~ goout + famrel + absences, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(model, type = "response")

library(dplyr)
# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   236   23
##    TRUE     67   44
# Computing the total proportion of inaccurately classified individuals
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong) 
}

inaccurately_classified <- loss_func(alc$high_use, alc$prediction)
inaccurately_classified
## [1] 0.2432432

To evaluate how our prediction is reliable, we provide the 2x2 cross tabulation of prediction versus the actual values. According to this table, for 236 + 44 = 280 cases, our model predicts the correct value. However, for 23 + 67 = 90 cases, its prediction is inaccurate. The loss function tells us the total proportion of inaccurately classified individuals are 0.24 percent. Comparing the prediction power of our model with a simple guessing strategy, our model considerably better predict the value because the training error is much less than 0.50 percent (0.24 < 0.50).

First, I showed the summaries of variables, then plotted the matrix of scatterplots by using pairs function. From matrix of scatterplots we can see a scatterplot for each pair of variables if we set them in a matrix. Then I showed the correlation between each pair of varibles by using the corrplot function. The Corrplot illustrates the positive relationship between pairs of variables with red color and negative relationship with blue color. The darker the colors, the stronger the relationship between the variables. The very dark blue color in the corplot relates to relationship between each variable with itself, which is the srtongest relationship but it is not a meaningful relationship.

Exersice 4

# standardize variables
boston_scaled <- scale(Boston)
boston_scaled <- as.data.frame(scale(Boston))

# scaled crime rate
boston_scaled$crim <- as.numeric(boston_scaled$crim)

# create a quantile vector of crim and print it
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)

# create a categorical variable 'crime'
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, labels = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))

# remove original crim from the dataset
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)

# add the new categorical value to scaled data
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

# number of rows in the Boston dataset 
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)

# choose randomly 80% of the rows
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)

# create train set
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]

# create test set 
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

# save the correct classes from test data
correct_classes <- boston_scaled$crime

# remove the crime variable from test data
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

To adjust the data set for further analysis, we need to standardize/scale the whole data set. We can do scaling because all variables in data set are numerical. In the scaling we subtract the column means from the corresponding columns and divide the difference with standard deviation. The scaled data become much smaller and even negative in some cases.

Exercise 5

# linear discriminant analysis
lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ . , data = train)

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(factor(train$crime))

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, col = classes, pch = classes, dimen = 2)

ind <- sample(nrow(boston_scaled),  size = nrow(boston_scaled) * 0.8)

table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)

While the most errors has been occurred in prediction of low category/label because table shows 13 correct labeled values, and 7 wrong labeled values in test set.

library(ggplot2)

# reload the data

# k-means clustering
km <- kmeans(Boston, centers = 4)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)

set.seed(123)

# determine the number of clusters
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(Boston, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')
## Warning: `qplot()` was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.

# k-means clustering
km <- kmeans(Boston, centers = 2)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)

comment: After calculating the total within sum of squares, we see two radical drops in qplot, then the optimal number of cluster is 2. Again we ran k-means algorithm with 2 clusters and saw the distribution of data for each pair of variables while divided into two clusters/categories, one cluster in red color and the other one in black color.
